5|$|In 1861, Charles Bright and Latimer Clark {{proposed}} {{the names of}} ohm, volt, and farad in honour of Georg Ohm, Alessandro Volta and Michael Faraday respectively for the practical units based on the <b>centimetre-gramme-second</b> absolute system. This was supported by Thomson (Lord Kelvin) These names were later scaled {{for use in the}} Practical System. The concept of naming units of measure after noteworthy scientists was subsequently used for other units.|$|E

